    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.18.13"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>  
                <fw type="curatorial"><del/><add>13</add></fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">SAINT MARY'S COLLEGE
                        <lb/>
                    NOTRE DAME
                        <lb/>
                    HOLY CROSS, INDIANA
                        <lb/>
                
                    OFFICE OF THE PRESIDENT</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>November 3, 1939.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>c/o Hotel Custer,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Galesburg, Illinois.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>You are truly good to remember your promise and fulfill it in the midst of your preoccupations with lectures. "In the Steps of Saint Francis" reached me some time ago. It promises an inspiring and exalted spiritual adventure with a mutual hero of ours.</p>
                
                <p>You left with us values comparable to those that you found here and to those that you took away in memory and in thought. Again and again we recur to what you said and to what you must be in order to speak as you do. We cannot be too grateful for your coming.</p>
                
                <p>I have just written to the President of our college in Salt Lake City. On hearing from her I shall write to Sigurd regarding your visit there. You will find it a magnificent setting for your lectures. The father of the President of the college was in the Custer wars. Your visit should be inspiring for all of you.</p>
                
                <p>I must advert to your touching request. When we come to the realization that our end in life is "to be used for some good purpose," we approximate the fulfillment of our prayer. Instrumentality is our great mission and God's need of us. How that knowledge exalts one and uplifts the most apparently useless existence to levels of divine cooperation! You make that profoundly evident to all who share your thought.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours most sincerely,</salute>
                    <signed>Sister M. Madeleva.</signed>
                
                    <note>SMM-SMG</note> 
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
